\title{Matrix ring has zero divisors}
\author{alex-nelson}
\import{notation}
\date{2025-12-17}
\taxon{example}

\p{Consider #{\varepsilon\in\Mat_{2}(\CC)} defined as
##{\varepsilon=\begin{pmatrix}0 & 1\\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}}
We see that #{\varepsilon^{2}=0}. Hence #{\varepsilon} is a zero divisor.}

\p{This example generalizes to any #{n\geq 2} and any unital [[ring-0001]] #{R} (with a single nonzero entry instead of #{1} for non-unital rings).}